{"cursor":"68112","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n planet Neptune (top) and its moon Triton (center), taken by Voyager 2 during\n its 1989 flyby]]\n\nThe 'definition ofplanet', since the word was coined by the ancient Greeks, has\nincluded within its scope a wide range of celestial bodies. Greek astronomers\nemployed the term asteres planetai (á¼ÏÏÎ­ÏÎµÏ ÏÎ»Î±Î½á¿ÏÎ±Î¹), \"wandering stars\", for\nobjects which apparently move over the sky. Over the millennia, the term has\nincluded a variety of different objects, from the Sun and the Moon to satellites\nand asteroids.\n\nBy the end of the 19th century the word planet, though it had yet to be defined,\nhad become a working term applied only to a small set of objects in the Solar\nSystem. After 1992, however, astronomers began to discover many additional\nobjects beyond the orbit of Neptune, as well as hundreds of objects orbiting\nother stars. These discoveries not only increased the number of potential\nplanets, but also expanded their variety and peculiarity. Some were nearly large\nenough to be stars, while others were smaller than Earth's moon. These\ndiscoveries challenged long-perceived notions of what a planet could be.\n\nThe issue of a clear definition for planet came to a head in 2005 with the\ndiscovery of the trans-Neptunian object Eris, a body larger than the smallest\nthen-accepted planet, Pluto. In its 2006 response, the International\nAstronomical Union (IAU), recognised by astronomers as the world body\nresponsible for resolving issues of nomenclature, released its decision on the\nmatter. This definition, which applies only to the Solar System, states that a\nplanet is a body that orbits the Sun, is massive enough for its own gravity to\nmake it round, and has \"cleared its neighbourhood\" of smaller objects around its\norbit. Under this new definition, Pluto and the other trans-Neptunian objects do\nnot qualify as planets. The IAU's decision has not resolved all controversies,\nand while many scientists have accepted the definition, some in the astronomical\ncommunity have rejected it outright.\n","linknr":967,"url":"Definition_of_planet","recorded":1362665472,"links":67,"instances":["astronomer","moon","moon","moon","moon","dwarf_planet","moon","moon","constellation","moon","moon","astronomy","moon","moon","dwarf_planet","moon","moon","cometary","planet","dwarf_planet","dwarf_planet","astronomer"],"pdf":["http://sd-www.jhuapl.edu/weaver_projects/GPD/Contributed_Talks/hilton_gpd_poster.pdf","http://sd-www.jhuapl.edu/weaver_projects/GPD/Contributed_Talks/hilton_gpd_poster.pdf","http://www.gps.caltech.edu/%7Embrown/papers/ps/xena.pdf","http://www.gps.caltech.edu/%7Embrown/papers/ps/xena.pdf","http://astro.cas.cz/nuncius/nsiii_09.pdf","http://astro.cas.cz/nuncius/nsiii_09.pdf","http://www.iau.org/static/resolutions/Resolution_GA26-5-6.pdf","http://www.iau.org/static/resolutions/Resolution_GA26-5-6.pdf","http://web.archive.org/web/20070205035336/http://www.cfa.harvard.edu/iau/special/08747.pdf","http://arxiv.org/pdf/1210.0305v1.pdf","http://arxiv.org/pdf/1210.0305v1.pdf","http://www.boulder.swri.edu/~hal/PDF/planet_def.pdf","http://www.boulder.swri.edu/~hal/PDF/planet_def.pdf","http://www.rni.helsinki.fi/~mjk/thirty.pdf","http://www.rni.helsinki.fi/~mjk/thirty.pdf"],"categories":["Planetary science","Planets of the Solar System","Planets","History of astronomy","Definitions|Planet","Definition of planet|","Astronomical controversies"],"headings":["History","IAU definition","Acceptance of the definition","Ongoing controversies","See also","Notes","References","Bibliography and external links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/e/e7/Cscr-featured.svg/15px-Cscr-featured.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2a/Voyager_2_Neptune_and_Triton.jpg/400px-Voyager_2_Neptune_and_Triton.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/common